item.title: How do i make a wild zone safe?
item.dc:creator: @Zach_93 Zach 93
item.description:
@Zach_93 wrote:

Asking to be spoon-fed on how to make a specific area have a specific function will not better you at programming. Reading the java API or the java tutorials might, reading the tutorials section just for the heck of it (this applies more for MITB than MSCP). You’re just making excuses.

The questions asked in this section are the same year after year. “Hao duz i leik make my st00f work kthx rep4help lolllll im new plz plz help help 0mgfg0m urgent!@@@@@@@@@eleven!2!1”, it’s ridiculous.

public boolean area(int x, int y) {
	if (x >= 1000 && x <= 1100 && y >= 2000 && y <= 2100) ||
	(x >= 1200 && x <= 1300 && y >= 2200 && y <= 2300) ||
	(x >= 1400 && x <= 1500 && y >= 2400 && y <= 2400) ||
	(x >= 1600 && y <= 1700 && y >= 2600 && y <= 2700) {
		return true;
	}
	return false;
}

These are completely made up values, by the way.

item.title: How do i make a wild zone safe?
item.dc:creator: @koopa_king koopa king
item.description:
@koopa_king wrote:

Pretty much what

 absX >= #### && absX <= ####

is saying is that any X value between the two numbers is safe.

Ex:

 absX >= 3493 && absX <= 3500

^ That means that any X-value between the value of 3493 and 3500 will be safe. Then you need to put in your Y-values so that you don’t just have a strip going across your map that is safe. So in fact, you are basically making a box for your safe area.

                       [v absY <= ####]
                       --------X---------
                       |                       |
                       |                       |

[absX >= #### >] X X [< absX <= ####]
| |
| |
--------X---------
[^ absY >= ####]

I hope my drawing makes it easy for you to understand it. =/

item.title: How do i make a wild zone safe?
item.dc:creator: @koopa_king koopa king
item.description:
@koopa_king wrote:

Go into your client.java file and hit ctrl + f.

Then type in

public boolean nonWild

Then when you see

|| (absX >= #### && absX <= #### && absY >= #### && absY<= ####)

You are in the right section. You then have to add in your own coordinates on what you want to be a safe zone. I will let you experiment with it seeing as I feel as if this is already a little bit too much help.
